You can actually create meaningful implementations of methods on nil pointers.<p><pre><code>    if b == nil {
        fmt.Println(&quot;:)&quot;)
    } else {
        fmt.Println(b.emote)
    }
</code></pre>
In this case, that&#x27;s useless, but that&#x27;s an artifact of the chosen example. I use it every so often in places where it happens to have meaning.<p>Go often treats nil as a legal value, which means that some of the things you might expect to crash don&#x27;t, and when used idiomatically can sometimes make for shorter code. For instance, the &quot;length&quot; call on slices will happily take a nil and return 0, you can &quot;append&quot; to a nil slice and get a slice back, etc. Ultimately it&#x27;s still a language with a null in it, though. There&#x27;s no non-nil pointer type.
